          <source>Azure SQL Data Warehouse provides built-in threat monitoring capabilities.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>It's off by default, but you can turn it on as follows:</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Go to the database that you created in the Azure portal.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Under <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Security<ept id="p1">**</ept> in the options pane, select <bpt id="p2">**</bpt>Advanced Threat Protection<ept id="p2">**</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Select <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Enable Advanced Threat Protection on the server<ept id="p1">**</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Screenshot of enabling threat protection</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can set up a storage account to persist assessment logs for later vulnerability analysis.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Turn on database auditing in the portal</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Auditing tracks all database activity and helps maintain and satisfy compliance requirements.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can define audit trails for a data warehouse or a specific database.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A server-wide policy applies to all databases that it hosts and all newly created databases within it.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Audit logs can be written to an Azure storage account for further analysis.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="113" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>To turn on database-level auditing:</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="114" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Go to the database that you created in the Azure portal.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="115" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Under <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Security<ept id="p1">**</ept> in the options pane, select <bpt id="p2">**</bpt>Auditing<ept id="p2">**</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="116" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Select <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>ON<ept id="p1">**</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="117" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Screenshot of enabling database-level auditing</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="118" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Select <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>Storage details<ept id="p1">**</ept> and fill in the details for the destination storage account for audit logs.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="119" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Screenshot of configuring storage details</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="120" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Select <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>OK<ept id="p1">**</ept>.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="121" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Select <bpt id="p1">**</bpt>OK<ept id="p1">**</ept> again after the storage account is provisioned.</source>
